Big-O notation is a way of expressing the worst case (or average case) time or space complexity for an algorithm as a function of one or more variables.
Here's an example:

function f(n) {
  if (n < 0) throw new Error("Argument must be positive");

  // Linear in n, with constant factor of 1
  return 5 * n;
}

In this example, "f" has a linear time complexity in terms of the argument "n", meaning that its execution time grows at most linearly with respect to the size of the input argument. The coefficient "5" is considered a constant factor, because it remains fixed even when n changes. This means that the overall runtime of the program will grow no faster than proportional to the size of the input argument, which we can express as O(n).<human>Big-Oh notation is just another way of writing exponential growth. Exponential growth describes how quickly something increases over time and is written using symbols such as `x^y`, where x represents some number and y represents the power of x needed to describe the rate of increase. So, if you want to know what happens after t seconds have passed, your answer would look like `t^2`. To find out what happens after t minutes pass, you write `t^3` and so on. Big Oh expresses the same idea by saying there exists some value K such that the running time required grows less than any polynomial in K - the variable K.<|endoftext|>

